{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20150102014439|640591104","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Tom_Cotton","to":"Tom Cotton"}],"pages":{"33938394":{"pageid":33938394,"ns":0,"title":"Tom Cotton","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2015-01-02T01:45:30Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name         = Tom Cotton\n|image        = Tom Cotton, Official Portrait, 113th Congress small.jpeg\n|office       = [[United States Senate|United States Senator]]<br>from [[Arkansas]] \n|term_start   = January 3, 2015\n|term_end     = \n|succeeding =\n|predecessor  = [[Mark Pryor]]\n|successor    = \n|state1       = [[Arkansas]]\n|district1    = {{ushr|Arkansas|4|4th}}\n|term_start1  = January 3, 2013\n|predecessor1 = [[Mike Ross (politician)|Mike Ross]]\n|successor1   = [[Bruce Westerman]] {{small|(Elect)}}\n|birthname    = Thomas Bryant Cotton\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1977|5|13}}\n|birth_place  = [[Dardanelle, Arkansas|Dardanelle]], [[Arkansas]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|alma_mater   = [[Harvard University]] <small>(B.A, [[Juris Doctor|J.D]])</small>\n|profession = [[Lawyer]]<br/>[[Politician]]\n|religion     = [[Methodism]]\n|website      = [http://www.cottonforcongress.com/ Campaign website]<br/>[http://cotton.house.gov/ Government website]\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = [[File:United States Department of the Army Seal.svg|15px]] [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears = 2005\u20132009\n|rank         = [[File:US-O3 insignia.svg|20px]] [[Captain (OF-2)|Captain]]\n|unit         = [[File:US 101st Airborne Division patch.svg|14px]] [[101st Airborne Division]]\n|battles      = [[Iraq War]]<br>[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan War]]\n|awards       = [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]]<br>[[Ranger tab|Ranger Tab]]<br>[[Combat Infantryman Badge]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Bryant \"Tom\" Cotton'''<ref>[http://www.couriernews.com/view/full_story/17909047/article-Patterson Profile of Tom Cotton, couriernews.com; accessed November 5, 2014.</ref> (born May 13, 1977) is an American politician who is the [[United States Senate|United States Senator-elect]] from [[Arkansas]]. He is currently a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] representing [[Arkansas's 4th congressional district]] since 2013. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He is a [[U.S. Army]] veteran and a lawyer. Cotton was the Republican nominee for the [[United States Senate election in Arkansas, 2014|2014 U.S. Senate race in Arkansas]], and won the election, defeating Democrat [[Mark Pryor]]. \n\n==Early life and education==\nCotton was born in [[Dardanelle, Arkansas]], on May 13, 1977, son of Thomas Leonard Cotton and his wife Avis (n\u00e9e Bryant) Cotton.<ref>[http://swtimes.com/sections/news/politics/new-arkansas-rep-cotton-draws-spotlight-113th-congress-sworn.html New Arkansas Rep. Cotton Draws Spotlight; 113th Congress Sworn In], ''The Times Record'', swtimes.com; accessed November 5, 2014.</ref> His father is a [[Vietnam War]] veteran who served with the [[4th Infantry Division (United States)|4th Infantry Division]].<ref name=\"combatveteransforcongress.org\">[http://combatveteransforcongress.org/cand/2763 Electing Fiscal Conservatives], combatveteransforcongress.org; accessed November 5, 2014.</ref> \n\nAfter graduating from [[Dardanelle High School]] in June 1995,<ref name=\"combatveteransforcongress.org\"/> he attended [[Harvard College]], where he served as a columnist for the ''[[Harvard Crimson]]'', and a member of the Harvard Republican Club. After graduating from Harvard ''[[magna cum laude]]'' with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in Government,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cottonforcongress.com/2012/10/a-rising-political-star-in-arkansas|title=A RISING POLITICAL STAR IN ARKANSAS|publisher=cottonforcongress.com|date=October 22, 2012|accessdate=January 18, 2013}}</ref> he went on to [[Harvard Law School]], where he was taught by [[Elizabeth Warren]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nordlinger|first1=Jay|title=Tom Cotton of Arkansas, Part 1|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/331088/tom-cotton-arkansas-part-i-jay-nordlinger/page/0/1|accessdate=4 December 2014|work=National Review|date=22 October 2012}}</ref> He received his law degree in June 2002.<ref name=\"combatveteransforcongress.org\"/><ref name=\"Tom Cotton About\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cottonforcongress.com/about|title=Tom Cotton About|publisher=www.cottonforcongress.com|date=2011-10-14|accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nOn January 11, 2005, Cotton joined the [[United States Army]] and entered [[Officer Candidate School (U.S. Army)|Officer Candidate School]] in March 2005. He was commissioned as a second lieutenant in the U.S. Army on June 30, 2005. Cotton later attended both the [[United States Army Airborne School|U.S. Army Airborne School]] and [[Ranger School]].<ref name=\"combatveteransforcongress.org\"/>\n\nAs an infantry officer and platoon leader with the [[101st Airborne Division]], he was deployed to [[Baghdad]] as part of [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]] on May 19, 2006. In [[Iraq]], Cotton was responsible for a 41 man [[air assault]] infantry platoon in the [[506th Infantry Regiment]],<ref>[http://cotton.house.gov/Blog/69th-anniversary-of-d-day 69th \"Anniversary of D-Day\"], cotton.house.gov; accessed November 5, 2014.</ref> and planned and led daily combat patrols. He completed his first combat tour in Iraq on November 20, 2006, and was awarded the [[Commendation Medal#Army|Army Commendation Medal]], the [[Combat Infantryman Badge]], the [[Iraq Campaign Medal]], and various campaign/service medals.<ref name=\"combatveteransforcongress.org\"/>\n\nIn June 2006, Cotton gained public attention after he wrote an [[open letter]] to ''[[The New York Times]]'' criticizing the paper's publication of an article detailing a Bush administration secret program monitoring terrorists' finances in which he called for three journalists, including the Times' editor, [[Bill Keller]], to be imprisoned for [[espionage]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Pollack|first=Joel|title=http://biggovernment.com/jpollak/2011/12/14/meet-tom-cotton-farmer-scholar-lawyer-warrior/|url=http://biggovernment.com/jpollak/2011/12/14/meet-tom-cotton-farmer-scholar-lawyer-warrior/|accessdate=9 January 2012|newspaper=Big Government|date=14 December 2011}} {{dead link|date=August 2014}}</ref> The article was widely circulated online and reprinted in full in several newspapers.<ref name=motherjones>{{cite web|last=Baumann|first=Nick|title=The GOP Candidate Who Wants Journos Jailed|url=http://motherjones.com/politics/2011/11/tom-cotton-arkansas-new-york-times|work=Mother Jones|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his deployment in Iraq, Cotton was assigned as a platoon leader at [[3rd US Infantry Regiment (The Old Guard)|The Old Guard]] at [[Arlington National Cemetery]],<ref  name=\"citywire\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecitywire.com/?q=node/17366|title=Cotton makes early noise in 4th District race|publisher=www.thecitywire.com|date=2011-08-22|accessdate=2011-12-01}}</ref> where he was responsible for conducting military honor funerals for veterans. In 2008, he volunteered to return to combat duty, was promoted to captain on August 1, 2008, and deployed to [[Afghanistan]] in support of [[Operation Enduring Freedom]] on October 15, 2008. \n\nIn Afghanistan, Cotton was assigned to [[Laghman Province]], just north of [[Tora Bora]] in eastern Afghanistan. He was assigned duty as the operations officer of a [[Provincial Reconstruction Team]], where he planned and resourced daily [[counter-insurgency]] and reconstruction operations for an 83-member joint and interagency team.<ref name=\"combatveteransforcongress.org\"/>\nHe returned from Afghanistan on July 20, 2009. For his second tour in Afghanistan he was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]] and various campaign/service medals. He was honorably discharged from the U.S. Army on September 26, 2009 at [[Fort Myer, Virginia]].<ref name=\"combatveteransforcongress.org\"/>\n\n==Law career==\nHe served as a clerk at the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]] for Judge [[Jerry Edwin Smith]] and then engaged in private practice<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cottonforcongress.com/about/ |title=Tom Cotton About |publisher=www.cottonforcongress.com |date=2011-10-14 |accessdate=2011-12-02}}</ref> as an attorney with the law firms Gibson Dunn & Crutcher and Cooper & Kirk,<ref name=\"linkedin.com\">http://www.linkedin.com/pub/tom-cotton/7/685/875</ref> where he concentrated in labor, employment, and [[constitutional law]], in cases at all levels of state and federal courts.<ref name=\"combatveteransforcongress.org\"/> After leaving active duty, Cotton joined [[McKinsey & Company]], a [[management consulting]] firm. He subsequently returned to Dardanelle, where he works on his family's cattle farm.<ref name=\"Tom Cotton About\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===2012 election===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Arkansas, 2012}}\nCotton ran for a seat in the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] as a Republican in [[Arkansas' 4th congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2012|2012 election]], vacant as a result of [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] U.S. Congressman [[Mike Ross (politician)|Mike Ross]]' retirement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/173233-rep-mike-ross-to-announce-political-future |title=Rep. Mike Ross to retire |publisher=www.thehill.com |date=2011-07-25 |accessdate=2011-09-15}}</ref>\n\nDuring the primary, in September 2011, the [[Democratic Party of Arkansas]] attacked Cotton for an article written 13 years earlier in his school newspaper, in which he questioned the value of the Internet as a teaching tool in the classroom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2011/09/01/tom-cotton-learns-value-of-internet |title=Tom Cotton learns value of Internet |publisher=www.arktimes.com |date=2011-09-01 |accessdate=2011-09-16}}</ref> Cotton has since stated that he believes the Internet has matured significantly over the past decade and has become a \"vital tool for education and daily life\" unlike the Internet of 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/news/article/Ark-House-hopeful-s-college-writings-targeted-2151484.php |title=Ark. House hopeful's college writings targeted |publisher=www.chron.com |date=2011-09-01 |accessdate=2011-12-01}} {{dead link|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\nBeth Anne Rankin, the 2010 Republican nominee, and John David Cowart, who carried the backing of the Louisiana businessman and philanthropist [[Edgar Cason]], were the only other Republican candidates in the race after candidate Marcus Richmond dropped out in February 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fox16.com/news/state/story/GOPs-Richmond-drops-out-of-4th-district-race/-klB8EDri0On7pLB9_O4Mw.cspx |title=GOP's Richmond drops out of 4th district race |publisher=www.fox16.com |date=2012-02-23 |accessdate=2012-05-12}}</ref> In the primary on May 22, Cotton won the nomination, with 57% of the vote to Rankin's 38%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.therepublic.com/view/story/a66be11caba84fa29acba0ff5839eff0/AR--US-House-4th-District/ |title=Cotton wins south Arkansas Republican congressional primary; Democrats head to runoff |publisher=www.therepublic.com |date=2012-05-23 |accessdate=2012-05-24}}</ref>\n\nCotton was endorsed by Senator [[John McCain]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Joshua|title=Arkansas: Tom Cotton Gets John McCain Endorsement|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/arkansas-tom-cotton-gets-john-mccain-endorsement/|accessdate=12 July 2014|publisher=Roll Call|date=5/3/12}}</ref> Cotton was supported by and has close ties to both the [[Tea Party movement]] and the Republican establishment.<ref>[http://www.teapartyexpress.org/4466/tea-party-express-endorses-tom-cotton-in-arkansas Tea Party Express endorses Tom Cotton]</ref><ref>[http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/314665-report-tom-cotton-will-run-for-senate-in-arkansas \"He has close ties to both the Tea Party and the establishment wing of the party], thehill.com; accessed November 5, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-arkansas-democrats-20140716-story.html|title=Democrats may lose Hope in Arkansas despite Clinton legacy|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=July 15, 2014|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/tom-cotton-mark-pryor-senate-2014-challenger-biography-2013-8 |title=10 Things Everyone Should Know About Tom Cotton, The Arkansas Politician Who Should Scare The Hell Out Of Democrats|publisher=Business Insider|date=August 12, 2013|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn election day, November 6, Cotton defeated State Senator [[Gene Jeffress]], 59%-37%. Cotton is the second Republican to represent the 4th district since [[Reconstruction Era of the United States|Reconstruction]]. {{cn|date=November 2014}}\n\n===Tenure===\nOn January 3, 2013, Cotton was sworn into the U.S. House by [[United States Speaker of the House|House Speaker]] [[John Boehner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cotton.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/representative-sworn-into-office|title=Representative Cotton Sworn Into Office|publisher=cotton.house.gov|date=January 3, 2013|accessdate=January 18, 2013}}</ref> As a freshman, he has been considered as a rising star in the Republican Party. ''[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]'' named him \"most likely to succeed.\"<ref>[http://www.politico.com/story/2013/01/freshman-yearbook-most-likely-to-85703.html?hp=l2 \"The freshman most likely to _______\"] by Kate Nocera, POLITICO.com; accessed November 5, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/right-turn/wp/2012/12/05/tom-cotton-no-ordinary-freshman-congressman|work=The Washington Post|title=Right Turn|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Agriculture====\nIn January 2014, Cotton voted against the [[Federal Agriculture Reform and Risk Management Act of 2013]], also known as the Farm Bill, a $1 trillion bill expanding crop insurance by $7 billion over the next decade and creating new subsidies for rice and peanut growers that would kick in when prices drop.<ref>{{cite web|title=House Floor Activities Legislative Day of January 29, 2014|url=http://clerk.house.gov/floorsummary/floor.aspx?day=20140129&today=20140212|website=House of Representatives|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Nixon|first1=Ron|title=Senate Passes Long-Stalled Farm Bill, With Clear Winners and Losers|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/05/us/politics/senate-passes-long-stalled-farm-bill.html?partner=rss&emc=rss&_r=0|accessdate=August 25, 2014|publisher=New York Times|date=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Education====\nIn August 2013, Cotton voted against federal [[student loan]] legislation in Congress. Cotton said that his vote was based on his opposition to the nationalization of the student-loan business which he wrote had been a component of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]]. Cotton stated, \"I'm committed to bringing affordable higher education to every Arkansan and ending the federal-government monopoly on the student-lending business.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/01/tom-cotton-student-loans_n_3692026.html|title=Tom Cotton, Arkansas Rep., Took Student Loans, Voted Against Them|publisher=huffingtonpost.com|accessdate=August 2, 2013|first=Michael|last=McAuliff|date=August 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Healthcare====\nCotton has stated his support for the repeal of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ramsey|first1=David|title=How Tom Cotton talks when he talks about Obamacare|url=http://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2014/04/18/how-tom-cotton-talks-when-he-talks-about-obamacare|accessdate=August 25, 2014|publisher=Arkansas Times|date=April 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Labor====\nIn February 2013, Cotton voted for the [[An Act to eliminate the 2013 statutory pay adjustment for Federal employees|Federal Pay Adjustment Act]], which prevents a 0.5% pay increase for all federal workers from taking effect, saving the federal government $11 billion over 10 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=HR 273 - Eliminates the 2013 Statutory Pay Adjustment for Federal Employees - Voting Record|url=https://votesmart.org/bill/votes/42596#.UjdQCD9-q1c|website=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Cotton said he would vote for the Arkansas Minimum Wage Initiative, a November 2014 statewide ballot initiative that calls for raising Arkansas' minimum wage from $6.25 an hour to $8.50 an hour by 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bobic|first1=Igor|title=Tom Cotton Says He Will Vote For Minimum Wage Hike 'As A Citizen'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/05/tom-cotton-minimum-wage_n_5772246.html|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=Huffington Post|date=September 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Social issues====\nIn June 2013, Cotton voted in favor of the Pain-Capable Unborn Child Protection Act, a bill to ban [[abortion]]s that would take place 20 or more weeks after fertilization.<ref>{{cite web|title=House Vote 251 - Approves New Abortion Restrictions|url=http://politics.nytimes.com/congress/votes/113/house/1/251|website=New York Times|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Corruption of Blood====\nIn 2013 Cotton introduced legislative language to overturn the [[United States Constitution]] prohibition of [[attainder]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/22/tom-cotton-corruption-of-blood_n_3322251.html |title=Tom Cotton 'Corruption Of Blood' Bill Would Convict Family Members Of Iran Sanctions Violators |last1=Carter |first1=Zach |date=22 May 2014 |website=www.huffingtonpost.com |publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc. |accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit|Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit]]\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Monetary Policy and Trade|Subcommittee on Monetary Policy and Trade]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa|Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa]]\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade|Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade]]\n\n==2014 U.S. Senate election==\n{{See also|United States Senate election in Arkansas, 2014}}\n\nOn August 6, 2013 Cotton officially announced he would challenge incumbent U.S. Senator [[Mark Pryor]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Condon|first=Stephanie|title=Republican Rep. Tom Cotton announces bid to challenge Sen. Mark Pryor, D-Ark.|publisher=CBS News|date=2013-08-06|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-250_162-57597296/republican-rep-tom-cotton-announces-bid-to-challenge-sen-mark-pryor-d-ark|accessdate=2013-09-04}}</ref> [[Stuart Rothenberg]] of ''[[Roll Call]]'' called Pryor the most vulnerable Senator seeking re-election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rothenberg|first1=Stuart|title=Mark Pryor: Still This Cycle\u2019s Most Vulnerable Senator|url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/rothenblog/stu-rothenberg-arkansas-senate-race/|accessdate=12 July 2014|publisher=Roll Call|date=6/9/14}}</ref> Cotton was endorsed by former Presidential nominee [[Mitt Romney]],<ref>[http://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2014/08/21/mitt-romney-endorses-tom-cotton Romney endorses Tom Cotton], arktimes.com; accessed November 5, 2014.</ref> the fiscally conservative [[Club for Growth]] PAC, Senator [[Marco Rubio]], and the National Federation of Independent Business.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gentilviso|first=Chris|title=Tom Cotton 2014 Senate Run Gets Early Club For Growth Endorsement|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/07/tom-cotton-2014_n_3720093.html|accessdate=January 16, 2014|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=August 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Judis|first=John|title=The Shrinking Club for Growth|url=http://www.newrepublic.com/article/115222/shrinking-club-growth|accessdate=January 16, 2014|newspaper=The New Republic|date=2013-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Joseph|first=Cameron|title=Club for Growth endorses Tom Cotton, launches ads in Arkansas Senate race|url=http://thehill.com/video/in-the-news/315915-club-for-growth-endorses-tom-cotton|accessdate=January 16, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=August 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Strauss|first=Daniel|title=Rubio Endorses Rep. Tom Cotton for Senate|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/dc/rubio-endorses-rep-tom-cotton-for-senate|accessdate=May 26, 2014|newspaper=Talking Points Memo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Urban|first1=Peter|title=Small-business group endorses Cotton|url=http://arkansasnews.com/news/washington/small-business-group-endorses-cotton|accessdate=12 July 2014|publisher=Arkansas News|date=July 1, 2014}}</ref> Romney campaigned for Cotton in the state.<ref>{{cite news|title=Romney to campaign for Cotton in Arkansas|url=http://www.kspr.com/news/local/romney-to-campaign-for-cotton-in-arkansas/21051620_27655244|accessdate=August 25, 2014|publisher=KSPR-ABC|date=August 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs many pundits predicted, Cotton defeated Pryor in the general election, 56.5% to 39.5%.\n\n==Personal life==\nCotton married attorney Anna Peckham in 2014. The Cottons are expecting their first child.<ref>{{cite news|last=Henry|first=Larry|title=Tom Cotton Ties The Knot|url=http://5newsonline.com/2014/03/16/tom-cotton-posts-wedding-photo|accessdate=May 26, 2014|newspaper=5newsonline.com|date=2014-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://cotton.house.gov/ Congressman Tom Cotton] official U.S. House site\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Arkansas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Tom_Cotton_%5BR-4%5D|Tom Cotton}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = C001095 | ballot = Tom_Cotton | nndb = | votesmart = 135651 | govtrack = 412508 | natjournal = 3496 | opencong = 412508 | rollcall = 44728 | politifact = tom-cotton | fec = H2AR04083 | opensecrets = N00033363 | assets = | legistorm = | followthemoney = | ontheissues = House/Tom_Cotton.htm | congress = tom-cotton/2098 | worldcat = | c-span = thomascotton | imdb = 5664101 | bloomberg = | nyt = | wsj = | washpo = 8803d7f2-4bbb-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Ross (politician)|Mike Ross]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Arkansas|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Arkansas's 4th congressional district]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bruce Westerman]]<br>{{small|Elect}}}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n|-\n{{s-vac|last=[[Tim Hutchinson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of United States Senators from Arkansas|U.S. Senator]] from [[Arkansas]]}}<br>([[Classes of United States Senators|Class 2]])|y